The paper proposes a processor-in-memory (PIM) solution for deep convolutional networks (ConvNets), which is a popular workload for servers and high-end embedded systems. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) or Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper focuses on Smart Memory Cubes (SMCs) and their use in a co-design approach, which could fall under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper also discusses energy efficiency and scalability, which could be relevant to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents a tiling mechanism for efficient computation, which could be related to the Architecture (cs.AR) sub-category.
